Hope for India
Cambridge, USA – India’s latest election may well be the most important positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Indian National Congress, which had ruled India almost uninterrupted since independence from Britain in 1947.
They might feel happy about this decision.
The leader of the Congress Party, Sonia Gandhi, widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, has been in effective control since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh was merely a figurehead.
In her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda with increased transfers, causing India's annual growth rate to fall below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP remains around $4,000, less than half that of China.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi campaigned on promises of rapid job and income growth across all of India, like he did as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state where economic activity expanded and attracted both domestic and foreign commercial investments.
A key feature of the latest election was the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) led by Modi achieving an absolute majority in the national parliament, which is arguably unprecedented in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will support Modi in his economic plans.
The new finance minister Arun Jaitley, politically experienced, served as a minister in the previous BJP government.
Jaitley is also known as a strategic thinker who is sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the governor of the Reserve Bank of India (central bank). Rajan, an outstanding economist, showed a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate during his tenure and tried to reform some productivity bottlenecks in India's financial sector.
To implement and see the effects of measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should look at progress in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
While India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small fraction of people can access the opportunities they provide because elementary and secondary education in India is very backward.
Only 60% of adult Indians have basic literacy skills.
Teachers themselves are inadequately educated and lack motivation, with many teachers not even showing up at their assigned schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products to the entire country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private air routes and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal consolidation.
<s>Massive budget deficits absorb national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that must be financed through future taxes.
<s>Privatization.
<s>The government-owned manufacturing and other industrial enterprises operate inefficiently, often leading to the consumption of national savings.
<s>Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
<s>Eliminate subsidies.
Electricity and energy subsidies lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, India's cash transfer system is quite efficient due to the implementation of a remarkable fingerprint-based cash transfer scheme.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government buys, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is that large quantities of goods are stored in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and zoning.
Just visit Mumbai or any major Indian city, and you'll see how zoning restrictions lead to poor urban land use and hinder sprawl.
Unclear property rights, especially in agriculture, prevent rural industrialization.
Relax foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions would strengthen the financial sector and play a significant role in economic growth.
Tax reforms.
India's complex central and state sales tax regime distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a federal system has gone on for a long time, and it is now time for implementation.
Corruption.
<s>Larger-scale corruption cases have undermined economic confidence and obstructed official decision-making.
<s>India also suffers from petty corruption, with bribes becoming a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
<s>The government should crack down on larger-scale corruption and limit petty corruption through new cash transfer programs.
<s>Pushed by stronger growth and expectations of rising profits, Indian stock markets have risen by 20% so far this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to prove to the world that they can deliver on their campaign promises.
